SIMPLE: inquest
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inquest
<hw>In"quest</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>enqueste</ets>, OF. <ets>enqueste</ets>, F.
<ets>enqu⟦ecir⟧te</ets>, LL. <ets>inquesta</ets>, for
<ets>inquisita</ets>, fr. L. <ets>inquisitus</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>inquirere</ets>. See <er>Inquire</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Inquiry; quest; search.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The laborious and vexatious <qex>inquest</qex> that the soul must
make after science.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Judicial inquiry;
official examination, esp. before a jury; <as>as, a coroner's
<ex>inquest</ex> in case of a sudden death</as>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>A body of men assembled under authority of law to inquire into any
matter, civil or criminal, particularly any case of violent or sudden
death; a jury, particularly a coroner's jury. The <xex>grand jury</xex>
is sometimes called the <xex>grand inquest</xex>. See under
<er>Grand</er>.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>The finding of the jury upon
such inquiry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Coroner's inquest</b></col>, <cd>an inquest held by a
coroner to determine the cause of any violent, sudden, or mysterious
death. See <er>Coroner</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Inquest of
office</b></col>, <cd>an inquiry made, by authority or direction of
proper officer, into matters affecting the rights and interests of the
crown or of the state.</cd> <rj><au>Craig. Bouvier.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inquiet</ent>⟦br⟧
